entry.title: Remove PDM::SaveImportedProfile().
entry.content:
Before explicit save dialogs, Autofill imported profiles silently on

form submit. This happened through the following calls:

- FormDataImporter::ImportAndProcessFormData() is called on form submit

to extract a profile from the submit form.

- The FormDataImporter calls AddressProfileSaveManager::

ImportProfileFromForm().

- The AddressProfileSaveManager calls PDM::SaveImportedProfile(), which

deduplicates the import candidate against the existing profiles and

potentially saves it. The merging happened in

AutofillProfileComparator::MergeProfile().



Since explicit save dialogs were launched, the flow looks different:

- From AddressProfileSaveManager::ImportProfileFromForm(), a

ProfileImportProcess is created, which is responsible for determining

the import type (new profile, update profile, duplicate, etc).

- Based on the ProfileImportProcess's decision, the

AddressProfileSaveManager triggers UI that shows the import dialog.

- Once the user made a decision, AddressProfileSaveManager::

FinalizeProfileImport() is called. Based on the user's decision, the

ProfileImportProcess::GetResultingProfiles() are calculated and

stored in the PDM. This happens using PDM::SetProfilesForAllSources(),

which overwrites all existing profiles the users has (this is

necessary because an import might trigger multiple silent updates).



As a result, PDM::SaveImportedProfile() and AutofillProfileComparator::

MergeProfile() are no longer used. They were replaced by PDM::

SetProfilesForAllSources() and ProfileImportProcess, respectively.



Right now, SaveImportedProfile() is only used for tests, since they

circumvent save dialogs by defaulting to the legacy implementation. This

is undesirable, because the merging logic has already diverged.

This CL rewrites the testing logic to use the new implementation (and

auto-accepts the prompts without ever showing the UI). As a result,

SaveImportedProfile(), all related legacy functions and numerous unit

tests can be removed.



This CL's main change happens in address_profile_save_manager.cc: There,

the main call to SaveImportedProfile() is removed and redirected to

the new code in tests.



As a nice side-effect, this saves ~3.5k of binary size.

entry.title: Reset BFCache NavigationRequest synchronously if it'll be restarted
entry.content:
This CL makes the following changes:

- If an old NavigationRequest is restarted (asynchronously) because of

the BFCache eviction, we reset it synchronously to ensure it never

outlives the RenderFrameHost.

- Since the old NavigationRequest is reset before the restarting task

is run, the task must be posted to the FrameTreeNode so that it is

not cancelled when the old NavigationRequest is destroyed.

- Between resetting the old NavigationRequest and restarting a new one,

the FrameTreeNode will not be in the loading state. This will cause

some failures in the browser tests that relies on WaitForLoadStop to

ensure the completion of history navigation. These tests have been

updated to use TestNavigationManager instead.

- If a NavigationRequest's method cause a eviction during a history

navigation, it will now return immediately to avoid use-after-free, as

the NavigationRequest itself is deleted synchronously.



For more information, please refer to https://docs.google.com/document/d/1bF1YeC6Bd0GGd-EEi0eBkNgWi4D0hC4AxzYuYmYzYak

entry.title: [MirrorSync] Batch update completed state after holding it for 0.3s
entry.content:
Although simple to describe, several factors needed to be

considered when implementing this feature:



-An entry's metadata might be pulled by Files app at any time.



-"completed" sync states only surface to Files app when pushed

from Ash. Pulling an entry's metadata never returns "completed".

It only ever returns "queued", "in progress", or "not found".



-It's not enough to update an entry's metadata with the last time

it transitioned to "completed". A rerender must be triggered 300ms

or more after that moment in order for that to be reflected in the UI.

A metadata reload is probably the ideal render trigger in this case

since the entry's metadata might have changed in that 300ms+

interval.



-The dismissing logic cannot be easily added to the UI layer

because list and grid view item can be removed from the DOM

and completely rerendered at any moment due to the current

implementation of our virtual list, so the DOM is not a reliable

source of truth for the past metadata state of a given entry (nor

is it an ellegant/ideal one, but in this case it doesn't even serve as

a hacky source of truth).



-Leaf (or close-to-leaf) components should remain as simple as

possible, meaning `xf-inline-status` should remain ignorant about

this dismissing logic unless it can be implemented with pure CSS.



-The redux store will eventually be the ideal place to add such logic

considering the given conditions, however, at the moment, it doesn't

support selector, meaning adding the full spectrum of metadata

updates to the store would trigger too many state update callbacks

since they are currently not filtered by topic of interested by selectors.



With these considerations in mind, the selected approach in this CL

was to annonatate entries with the time when they transition to

completed and blocking them from receiving any redundant sync

status updates - i.e., blocking "completed" -> "completed" transitions.



In addition to annotating those entries when they completed, they are

also added to a list of entries that should be eventually updated (so

that their "completed" state is dismissed - i.e., updated to

"not_found", "queued", or "in progress" by getting its updated

metadata).



Finally, in intervals of 200ms, a routine verifies if any of the saved

completed entries have been updated more than 300ms ago and

are still being tracked in the first place (i.e., the user might

navigate away from the current directory, in which case there's no need

to update the file's sync status. Whenever this navigation happens,

the store reflects this by removing the previous directory entries

from its `allEntries` slice). When a given file passes those conditions,

the routine takes care of updating the file's metadata, which then

triggers a rerender of its item in the list/grid view, effectively

dismissing the completed state (or updating it to "queued" or

"in progress" in cases where the user, for example, was editing

the file and saved it shortly after it completed syncing).

"Multi-user sign-in" feature. Currently it checks if any logged in

user is managed which blocks copy or moves if only a single managed

user is logged in. This is fixed by explicitly verifying if we are

in a "Multi-user sign-in" case using the number of logged in users.

Not allowing a single logged-in managed user to use ODFS is already

handled by `IsEligibleAndEnabledUploadOfficeToCloud()`.

entry.title: ash::LaunchSystemWebAppAsync: Wait for SWA registration
entry.content:
When ash::LaunchSystemWebAppAsync gets called very early after startup

(e.g. in tests), the SWA registration process may not yet be complete,

in which case it used to do nothing. Callers who wanted to make sure

that their app launch succeeds had to explicitly wait for SWA

registration before calling LaunchSystemWebAppAsync. To do so, they

needed to first obtain the SystemWebAppManager. However, the

SystemWebAppManager for the given profile may not exist, because

LaunchSystemWebAppAsync actually uses a different profile in some

situations. There is no good way for callers to obtain that target

profile, and it's undesired to expose such a function.



Solve this by making LaunchSystemWebAppAsync wait for SWA registration.

entry.title: increase timeout of chrome-eve-chromeos
entry.content:
With the growing number of HW tests, the builder's max shard time is now

exceeding 3 hrs.



E.g., shard #2 in https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chrome/builders/ci/chromeos-eve-chrome/26517/overview.



Using hash-sharding helps to reduce the max shard time, but it

significantly increased the total runtime.



As the future will be migrating all existing CI builders to skylab

bulders, it is not worth doing shard optimization to the existing test

suites, e.g., creating separate crostini suites, since the sharding

in skylab builders is better.



Before the migration, increasing the timeout as a short-term solution.
